  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under **federal law** in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The penalties are outlined in the **Money Laundering Control Act (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957)** and vary depending on the specific violation, the amount of money involved, and other factors. Here are the key penalties:\n\n### 1. **Criminal Penalties for Money Laundering (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956):**\n   - **Imprisonment:** Up to **20 years** per violation.\n   - **Fines:** The greater of **$500,000** or **twice the value of the monetary instrument or funds involved** in the transaction.\n   - **Forfeiture:** The government can seize property involved in or traceable to the money laundering activity.\n\n### 2. **Criminal Penalties for Monetary Transactions Involving Illegally Derived Funds (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957):**\n   - **Imprisonment:** Up to **10 years** per violation.\n   - **Fines:** The greater of **$250,000** or **twice the value of the funds involved** in the transaction.\n   - **Forfeiture:** Property involved in the transaction may be subject to forfeiture.\n\n### 3. **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Circumstances:**\n   - If the money laundering activity involves funds derived from specified unlawful activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, or organized crime), penalties can be more severe.\n   - Repeat offenders or cases involving large sums of money may also face enhanced penalties.\n\n### 4. **Civil Penalties:**\n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities can face civil fines of up to **$10,000 or the value of the funds involved**, whichever is greater.\n\n### 5. **Other Consequences:**\n   - Conviction for money laundering can also result in **loss of professional licenses**, reputational damage, and restrictions on future financial activities.\n\n### 6. **Attempts and Conspiracy:**\n   - Even an **attempt** or **conspiracy** to commit money laundering can result in the same penalties as the completed offense.\n\nMoney laundering is aggressively prosecuted, and federal agencies like the **Department of Justice (DOJ)**, **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**, and **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)** work together to investigate and prosecute these cases.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
